# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mixture-models-em
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In statistics, an **expectation–maximization** (**EM**) **algorithm** is an iterative method to find (local) maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates of parameters in statistical models, where the model depends on unobserved latent variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] These parameter-estimates are then used to determine the distribution of the latent variables in the next E step.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It can be used, for example, to estimate a mixture of gaussians, or to solve the multiple linear regression problem.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm was explained and given its name in a classic 1977 paper by Arthur Dempster, Nan Laird, and Donald Rubin.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] They pointed out that the method had been "proposed many times in special circumstances" by earlier authors.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] One of the earliest is the gene-counting method for estimating allele frequencies by Cedric Smith.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hartley in 1958, and Hartley and Hocking in 1977, from which many of the ideas in the Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper originated.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Another one by S.K Ng, Thriyambakam Krishnan and G.J McLachlan in 1977.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hartley's ideas can be broadened to any grouped discrete distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A very detailed treatment of the EM method for exponential families was published by Rolf Sundberg in his thesis and several papers, following his collaboration with Per Martin-Löf and Anders Martin-Löf.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper in 1977 generalized the method and sketched a convergence analysis for a wider class of problems.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper established the EM method as an important tool of statistical analysis.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The convergence analysis of the Dempster–Laird–Rubin algorithm was flawed and a correct convergence analysis was published by C.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Wu's proof established the EM method's convergence also outside of the exponential family, as claimed by Dempster–Laird–Rubin.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm is used to find (local) maximum likelihood parameters of a statistical model in cases where the equations cannot be solved directly.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Typically these models involve latent variables in addition to unknown parameters and known data observations.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] That is, either missing values exist among the data, or the model can be formulated more simply by assuming the existence of further unobserved data points.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For example, a mixture model can be described more simply by assuming that each observed data point has a corresponding unobserved data point, or latent variable, specifying the mixture component to which each data point belongs.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Finding a maximum likelihood solution typically requires taking the derivatives of the likelihood function with respect to all the unknown values, the parameters and the latent variables, and simultaneously solving the resulting equations.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In statistical models with latent variables, this is usually impossible.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Instead, the result is typically a set of interlocking equations in which the solution to the parameters requires the values of the latent variables and vice versa, but substituting one set of equations into the other produces an unsolvable equation.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm proceeds from the observation that there is a way to solve these two sets of equations numerically.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] One can simply pick arbitrary values for one of the two sets of unknowns, use them to estimate the second set, then use these new values to find a better estimate of the first set, and then keep alternating between the two until the resulting values both converge to fixed points.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It's not obvious that this will work, but it can be proven in this context.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Additionally, it can be proven that the derivative of the likelihood is (arbitrarily close to) zero at that point, which in turn means that the point is either a local maximum or a saddle point.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In general, multiple maxima may occur, with no guarantee that the global maximum will be found.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Some likelihoods also have singularities in them, i.e., nonsensical maxima.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For example, one of the *solutions* that may be found by EM in a mixture model involves setting one of the components to have zero variance and the mean parameter for the same component to be equal to one of the data points.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, this quantity is often intractable since $\mathbf {Z}$ is unobserved and the distribution of $\mathbf {Z}$ is unknown before attaining ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The missing values (aka latent variables) $\mathbf {Z}$ are discrete, drawn from a fixed number of values, and with one latent variable per observed unit.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The parameters are continuous, and are of two kinds: Parameters that are associated with all data points, and those associated with a specific value of a latent variable (i.e., associated with all data points whose corresponding latent variable has that value).
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, it is possible to apply EM to other sorts of models.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Compute the probability of each possible value of ⁠ $\mathbf {Z}$ ⁠, given ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ ⁠.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Then, use the just-computed values of $\mathbf {Z}$ to compute a better estimate for the parameters ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ ⁠.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Iterate steps 2 and 3 until convergence.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The algorithm as just described monotonically approaches a local minimum of the cost function.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Although an EM iteration does increase the observed data (i.e., marginal) likelihood function, no guarantee exists that the sequence converges to a maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For multimodal distributions, this means that an EM algorithm may converge to a local maximum of the observed data likelihood function, depending on starting values.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A variety of heuristic or metaheuristic approaches exist to escape a local maximum, such as random-restart hill climbing (starting with several different random initial estimates ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}^{(t)}$ ⁠), or applying simulated annealing methods.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM is especially useful when the likelihood is an exponential family, see Sundberg (2019, Ch.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] 8) for a comprehensive treatment: the E step becomes the sum of expectations of sufficient statistics, and the M step involves maximizing a linear function.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In such a case, it is usually possible to derive closed-form expression updates for each step, using the Sundberg formula (proved and published by Rolf Sundberg, based on unpublished results of Per Martin-Löf and Anders Martin-Löf).
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM method was modified to compute maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates for Bayesian inference in the original paper by Dempster, Laird, and Rubin.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Other methods exist to find maximum likelihood estimates, such as gradient descent, conjugate gradient, or variants of the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Unlike EM, such methods typically require the evaluation of first and/or second derivatives of the likelihood function.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Expectation-Maximization works to improve $Q({\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }}^{(t)})$ rather than directly improving $\log p(\mathbf {X} \mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Here it is shown that improvements to the former imply improvements to the latter.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm can be viewed as two alternating maximization steps, that is, as an example of coordinate descent.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Consider the function: $F(q,\theta ):=\operatorname {E} _{q}[\log L(\theta ;x,Z)]+H(q),$ where q is an arbitrary probability distribution over the unobserved data z and *H*(*q*) is the entropy of the distribution q.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A Kalman filter is typically used for on-line state estimation and a minimum-variance smoother may be employed for off-line or batch state estimation.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, these minimum-variance solutions require estimates of the state-space model parameters.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM algorithms can be used for solving joint state and parameter estimation problems.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Operate a Kalman filter or a minimum-variance smoother designed with current parameter estimates to obtain updated state estimates.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Use the filtered or smoothed state estimates within maximum-likelihood calculations to obtain updated parameter estimates.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Suppose that a Kalman filter or minimum-variance smoother operates on measurements of a single-input-single-output system that possess additive white noise.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where ${\widehat {x}}_{k}$ are scalar output estimates calculated by a filter or a smoother from N scalar measurements $z_{k}$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The above update can also be applied to updating a Poisson measurement noise intensity.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where ${\widehat {x}}_{k}$ and ${\widehat {x}}_{k+1}$ are scalar state estimates calculated by a filter or a smoother.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The convergence of parameter estimates such as those above are well studied.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A number of methods have been proposed to accelerate the sometimes slow convergence of the EM algorithm, such as those using conjugate gradient and modified Newton's methods (Newton–Raphson).
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Also, EM can be used with constrained estimation methods.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This idea is further extended in *generalized expectation maximization (GEM)* algorithm, in which is sought only an increase in the objective function F for both the E step and M step as described in the As a maximization–maximization procedure section.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] GEM is further developed in a distributed environment and shows promising results.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It is also possible to consider the EM algorithm as a subclass of the **MM** (Majorize/Minimize or Minorize/Maximize, depending on context) algorithm, and therefore use any machinery developed in the more general case.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Q-function used in the EM algorithm is based on the log likelihood.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Therefore, it is regarded as the log-EM algorithm.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The use of the log likelihood can be generalized to that of the α-log likelihood ratio.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Then, the α-log likelihood ratio of the observed data can be exactly expressed as equality by using the Q-function of the α-log likelihood ratio and the α-divergence.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Obtaining this Q-function is a generalized E step.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Its maximization is a generalized M step.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This pair is called the α-EM algorithm which contains the log-EM algorithm as its subclass.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Thus, the α-EM algorithm by Yasuo Matsuyama is an exact generalization of the log-EM algorithm.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] No computation of gradient or Hessian matrix is needed.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The α-EM shows faster convergence than the log-EM algorithm by choosing an appropriate α.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The α-EM algorithm leads to a faster version of the Hidden Markov model estimation algorithm α-HMM.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM is a partially non-Bayesian, maximum likelihood method.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Its final result gives a probability distribution over the latent variables (in the Bayesian style) together with a point estimate for θ (either a maximum likelihood estimate or a posterior mode).
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A fully Bayesian version of this may be wanted, giving a probability distribution over θ and the latent variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Bayesian approach to inference is simply to treat θ as another latent variable.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In this paradigm, the distinction between the E and M steps disappears.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] If using the factorized Q approximation as described above (variational Bayes), solving can iterate over each latent variable (now including θ) and optimize them one at a time.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Now, k steps per iteration are needed, where k is the number of latent variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For graphical models this is easy to do as each variable's new Q depends only on its Markov blanket, so local message passing can be used for efficient inference.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In information geometry, the E step and the M step are interpreted as projections under dual affine connections, called the e-connection and the m-connection; the Kullback–Leibler divergence can also be understood in these terms.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where $\mathbb {I}$ is an indicator function and f is the probability density function of a multivariate normal.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In the last equality, for each i, one indicator $\mathbb {I} (z_{i}=j)$ is equal to zero, and one indicator is equal to one.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] These are called the "membership probabilities", which are normally considered the output of the E step (although this is not the Q function of below).
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Everything in the E step is known before the step is taken except $T_{j,i}$ , which is computed according to the equation at the beginning of the E step section.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This full conditional expectation does not need to be calculated in one step, because τ and ***μ***/**Σ** appear in separate linear terms and can thus be maximized independently.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] $Q(\theta \mid \theta ^{(t)})$ being quadratic in form means that determining the maximizing values of $\theta$ is relatively straightforward.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Also, $\tau$ , $({\boldsymbol {\mu }}_{1},\Sigma _{1})$ and $({\boldsymbol {\mu }}_{2},\Sigma _{2})$ may all be maximized independently since they all appear in separate linear terms.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Conclude the iterative process if the expectation update is sufficiently small.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The algorithm illustrated above can be generalized for mixtures of more than two multivariate normal distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm has been implemented in the case where an underlying linear regression model exists explaining the variation of some quantity, but where the values actually observed are censored or truncated versions of those represented in the model.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Special cases of this model include censored or truncated observations from one normal distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM typically converges to a local optimum, not necessarily the global optimum, with no bound on the convergence rate in general.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It is possible that it can be arbitrarily poor in high dimensions and there can be an exponential number of local optima.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hence, a need exists for alternative methods for guaranteed learning, especially in the high-dimensional setting.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Alternatives to EM exist with better guarantees for consistency, which are termed *moment-based approaches* or the so-called *spectral techniques*.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Moment-based approaches to learning the parameters of a probabilistic model enjoy guarantees such as global convergence under certain conditions unlike EM which is often plagued by the issue of getting stuck in local optima.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Algorithms with guarantees for learning can be derived for a number of important models such as mixture models, HMMs etc.
[src:mixture-models-em/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For these spectral methods, no spurious local optima occur, and the true parameters can be consistently estimated under some regularity conditions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In statistics, a **mixture model** is a probabilistic model for representing the presence of subpopulations within an overall population, without requiring that an observed data set should identify the sub-population to which an individual observation belongs.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Formally a mixture model corresponds to the mixture distribution that represents the probability distribution of observations in the overall population.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models are used for clustering, under the name model-based clustering, and also for density estimation.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models should not be confused with models for compositional data, i.e., data whose components are constrained to sum to a constant value (1, 100%, etc.).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] However, compositional models can be thought of as mixture models, where members of the population are sampled at random.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Conversely, mixture models can be thought of as compositional models, where the total size reading population has been normalized to 1.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In addition, in a Bayesian setting, the mixture weights and parameters will themselves be random variables, and prior distributions will be placed over the variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In such a case, the weights are typically viewed as a *K*-dimensional random vector drawn from a Dirichlet distribution (the conjugate prior of the categorical distribution), and the parameters will be distributed according to their respective conjugate priors.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] This characterization uses *F* and *H* to describe arbitrary distributions over observations and parameters, respectively.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Typically *H* will be the conjugate prior of *F*.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The two most common choices of *F* are Gaussian aka "normal" (for real-valued observations) and categorical (for discrete observations).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A Bayesian Gaussian mixture model is commonly extended to fit a vector of unknown parameters (denoted in bold), or multivariate normal distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] To incorporate this prior into a Bayesian estimation, the prior is multiplied with the known distribution $p({\boldsymbol {x|\theta }})$ of the data ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ conditioned on the parameters ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ to be estimated.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Although EM-based parameter updates are well-established, providing the initial estimates for these parameters is currently an area of active research.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Note that this formulation yields a closed-form solution to the complete posterior distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Estimations of the random variable ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ may be obtained via one of several estimators, such as the mean or maximum of the posterior distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Such distributions are useful for assuming patch-wise shapes of images and clusters, for example.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In the case of image representation, each Gaussian may be tilted, expanded, and warped according to the covariance matrices ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}_{i}$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] One Gaussian distribution of the set is fit to each patch (usually of size 8×8 pixels) in the image.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Notably, any distribution of points around a cluster (see *k*-means) may be accurately given enough Gaussian components, but scarcely over *K*=20 components are needed to accurately model a given image distribution or cluster of data.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Financial returns often behave differently in normal situations and during crisis times.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A mixture model for return data seems reasonable.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Sometimes the model used is a jump-diffusion model, or as a mixture of two normal distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] See Financial economics § Challenges and criticism and Financial risk management § Banking for further context.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Assume that we observe the prices of *N* different houses.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Different types of houses in different neighborhoods will have vastly different prices, but the price of a particular type of house in a particular neighborhood (e.g., three-bedroom house in moderately upscale neighborhood) will tend to cluster fairly closely around the mean.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Fitting this model to observed prices, e.g., using the expectation-maximization algorithm, would tend to cluster the prices according to house type/neighborhood and reveal the spread of prices in each type/neighborhood.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Assume that a document is composed of *N* different words from a total vocabulary of size *V*, where each word corresponds to one of *K* possible topics.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The distribution of such words could be modelled as a mixture of *K* different *V*-dimensional categorical distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A model of this sort is commonly termed a topic model.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Note that expectation maximization applied to such a model will typically fail to produce realistic results, due (among other things) to the excessive number of parameters.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Some sorts of additional assumptions are typically necessary to get good results.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Some sort of additional constraint is placed over the topic identities of words, to take advantage of natural clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The following example is based on an example in Christopher M.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Bishop, *Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning*.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Imagine that we are given an *N*×*N* black-and-white image that is known to be a scan of a hand-written digit between 0 and 9, but we don't know which digit is written.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] We can create a mixture model with $K=10$ different components, where each component is a vector of size $N^{2}$ of Bernoulli distributions (one per pixel).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Such a model can be trained with the expectation-maximization algorithm on an unlabeled set of hand-written digits, and will effectively cluster the images according to the digit being written.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The same model could then be used to recognize the digit of another image simply by holding the parameters constant, computing the probability of the new image for each possible digit (a trivial calculation), and returning the digit that generated the highest probability.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models apply in the problem of directing multiple projectiles at a target (as in air, land, or sea defense applications), where the physical and/or statistical characteristics of the projectiles differ within the multiple projectiles.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] An example might be shots from multiple munitions types or shots from multiple locations directed at one target.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The combination of projectile types may be characterized as a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Further, a well-known measure of accuracy for a group of projectiles is the circular error probable (CEP), which is the number *R* such that, on average, half of the group of projectiles falls within the circle of radius *R* about the target point.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model can be used to determine (or estimate) the value *R*.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model properly captures the different types of projectiles.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The financial example above is one direct application of the mixture model, a situation in which we assume an underlying mechanism so that each observation belongs to one of some number of different sources or categories.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] This underlying mechanism may or may not, however, be observable.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In this form of mixture, each of the sources is described by a component probability density function, and its mixture weight is the probability that an observation comes from this component.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In an indirect application of the mixture model we do not assume such a mechanism.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model is simply used for its mathematical flexibilities.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] For example, a mixture of two normal distributions with different means may result in a density with two modes, which is not modeled by standard parametric distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Another example is given by the possibility of mixture distributions to model fatter tails than the basic Gaussian ones, so as to be a candidate for modeling more extreme events.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model-based clustering is also predominantly used in identifying the state of the machine in predictive maintenance.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Density plots are used to analyze the density of high dimensional features.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] If multi-model densities are observed, then it is assumed that a finite set of densities are formed by a finite set of normal mixtures.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A multivariate Gaussian mixture model is used to cluster the feature data into k number of groups where k represents each state of the machine.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The machine state can be a normal state, power off state, or faulty state.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Each formed cluster can be diagnosed using techniques such as spectral analysis.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In the recent years, this has also been widely used in other areas such as early fault detection.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In image processing and computer vision, traditional image segmentation models often assign to one pixel only one exclusive pattern.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In fuzzy or soft segmentation, any pattern can have certain "ownership" over any single pixel.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] If the patterns are Gaussian, fuzzy segmentation naturally results in Gaussian mixtures.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Combined with other analytic or geometric tools (e.g., phase transitions over diffusive boundaries), such spatially regularized mixture models could lead to more realistic and computationally efficient segmentation methods.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Probabilistic mixture models such as Gaussian mixture models (GMM) are used to resolve point set registration problems in image processing and computer vision fields.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] For pair-wise point set registration, one point set is regarded as the centroids of mixture models, and the other point set is regarded as data points (observations).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] State-of-the-art methods are e.g. coherent point drift (CPD) and Student's t-distribution mixture models (TMM).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models are widely used in the social sciences to cluster observational data and identify latent group structure in complex, heterogeneous populations.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In studies of armed conflict, unsupervised mixture-model-based clustering has been applied to conflict event data to group observations into empirically derived conflict types without relying on predefined categories.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Such analyses reveal systematic differences across clusters in geographic, demographic, economic and infrastructural characteristics, corresponding to distinct conflict archetypes associated with different population and development profiles.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] This is one of the numerous examples of how mixture models can support data-driven classification in social science research.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Identifiability refers to the existence of a unique characterization for any one of the models in the class (family) being considered.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Estimation procedures may not be well-defined and asymptotic theory may not hold if a model is not identifiable.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Let *J* be the class of all binomial distributions with *n* = 2.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Clearly, given *p*0 and *p*1, it is not possible to determine the above mixture model uniquely, as there are three parameters (*π*, *θ*1, *θ*2) to be determined.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Consider a mixture of parametric distributions of the same class.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] be the class of all component distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Parametric mixture models are often used when we know the distribution *Y* and we can sample from *X*, but we would like to determine the *ai* and *θi* values.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Such situations can arise in studies in which we sample from a population that is composed of several distinct subpopulations.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] It is common to think of probability mixture modeling as a missing data problem.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] One way to understand this is to assume that the data points under consideration have "membership" in one of the distributions we are using to model the data.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] When we start, this membership is unknown, or missing.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The job of estimation is to devise appropriate parameters for the model functions we choose, with the connection to the data points being represented as their membership in the individual model distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A variety of approaches to the problem of mixture decomposition have been proposed, many of which focus on maximum likelihood methods such as expectation maximization (EM) or maximum *a posteriori* estimation (MAP).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Generally these methods consider separately the questions of system identification and parameter estimation; methods to determine the number and functional form of components within a mixture are distinguished from methods to estimate the corresponding parameter values.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Some notable departures are the graphical methods as outlined in Tarter and Lock and more recently minimum message length (MML) techniques such as Figueiredo and Jain and to some extent the moment matching pattern analysis routines suggested by McWilliam and Loh (2009).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Expectation maximization (EM) is seemingly the most popular technique used to determine the parameters of a mixture with an *a priori* given number of components.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] This is a particular way of implementing maximum likelihood estimation for this problem.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Thus on the basis of the current estimate for the parameters, the conditional probability for a given observation *x*(*t*) being generated from state *s* is determined for each *t* = 1, …, *N* ; *N* being the sample size.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The parameters are then updated such that the new component weights correspond to the average conditional probability and each component mean and covariance is the component specific weighted average of the mean and covariance of the entire sample.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Dempster also showed that each successive EM iteration will not decrease the likelihood, a property not shared by other gradient based maximization techniques.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Moreover, EM naturally embeds within it constraints on the probability vector, and for sufficiently large sample sizes positive definiteness of the covariance iterates.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] This is a key advantage since explicitly constrained methods incur extra computational costs to check and maintain appropriate values.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Theoretically EM is a first-order algorithm and as such converges slowly to a fixed-point solution.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Redner and Walker (1984) make this point arguing in favour of superlinear and second order Newton and quasi-Newton methods and reporting slow convergence in EM on the basis of their empirical tests.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] They do concede that convergence in likelihood was rapid even if convergence in the parameter values themselves was not.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The relative merits of EM and other algorithms vis-à-vis convergence have been discussed in other literature.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Other common objections to the use of EM are that it has a propensity to spuriously identify local maxima, as well as displaying sensitivity to initial values.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Figueiredo and Jain note that convergence to 'meaningless' parameter values obtained at the boundary (where regularity conditions breakdown, e.g., Ghosh and Sen (1985)) is frequently observed when the number of model components exceeds the optimal/true one.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] On this basis they suggest a unified approach to estimation and identification in which the initial *n* is chosen to greatly exceed the expected optimal value.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Their optimization routine is constructed via a minimum message length (MML) criterion that effectively eliminates a candidate component if there is insufficient information to support it.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In this way it is possible to systematize reductions in *n* and consider estimation and identification jointly.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] With initial guesses for the parameters of our mixture model, "partial membership" of each data point in each constituent distribution is computed by calculating expectation values for the membership variables of each data point.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] With expectation values in hand for group membership, plug-in estimates are recomputed for the distribution parameters.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixing coefficients *ai* are the means of the membership values over the *N* data points.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The component model parameters *θi* are also calculated by expectation maximization using data points *xj* that have been weighted using the membership values.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] With new estimates for *ai* and the *θi'*s, the expectation step is repeated to recompute new membership values.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The entire procedure is repeated until model parameters converge.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] As an alternative to the EM algorithm, the mixture model parameters can be deduced using posterior sampling as indicated by Bayes' theorem.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] This is still regarded as an incomplete data problem in which membership of data points is the missing data.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A two-step iterative procedure known as Gibbs sampling can be used.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The previous example of a mixture of two Gaussian distributions can demonstrate how the method works.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] As before, initial guesses of the parameters for the mixture model are made.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Instead of computing partial memberships for each elemental distribution, a membership value for each data point is drawn from a Bernoulli distribution (that is, it will be assigned to either the first or the second Gaussian).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The Bernoulli parameter *θ* is determined for each data point on the basis of one of the constituent distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Draws from the distribution generate membership associations for each data point.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Plug-in estimators can then be used as in the M step of EM to generate a new set of mixture model parameters, and the binomial draw step repeated.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The method of moment matching is one of the oldest techniques for determining the mixture parameters dating back to Karl Pearson's seminal work of 1894.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In this approach the parameters of the mixture are determined such that the composite distribution has moments matching some given value.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In many instances extraction of solutions to the moment equations may present non-trivial algebraic or computational problems.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Moreover, numerical analysis by Day has indicated that such methods may be inefficient compared to EM.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Nonetheless, there has been renewed interest in this method, e.g., Craigmile and Titterington (1998) and Wang.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] McWilliam and Loh (2009) consider the characterisation of a hyper-cuboid normal mixture copula in large dimensional systems for which EM would be computationally prohibitive.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Here a pattern analysis routine is used to generate multivariate tail-dependencies consistent with a set of univariate and (in some sense) bivariate moments.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The performance of this method is then evaluated using equity log-return data with Kolmogorov–Smirnov test statistics suggesting a good descriptive fit.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Some problems in mixture model estimation can be solved using spectral methods.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In particular it becomes useful if data points *xi* are points in high-dimensional real space, and the hidden distributions are known to be log-concave (such as Gaussian distribution or Exponential distribution).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Spectral methods of learning mixture models are based on the use of Singular Value Decomposition of a matrix which contains data points.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The idea is to consider the top *k* singular vectors, where *k* is the number of distributions to be learned.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The projection of each data point to a linear subspace spanned by those vectors groups points originating from the same distribution very close together, while points from different distributions stay far apart.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] One distinctive feature of the spectral method is that it allows us to prove that if distributions satisfy certain separation condition (e.g., not too close), then the estimated mixture will be very close to the true one with high probability.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Tarter and Lock describe a graphical approach to mixture identification in which a kernel function is applied to an empirical frequency plot so to reduce intra-component variance.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In this way one may more readily identify components having differing means.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] While this *λ*-method does not require prior knowledge of the number or functional form of the components its success does rely on the choice of the kernel parameters which to some extent implicitly embeds assumptions about the component structure.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Some of them can even probably learn mixtures of heavy-tailed distributions including those with infinite variance (see links to papers below).
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In this setting, EM based methods would not work, since the Expectation step would diverge due to presence of outliers.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] For each *i*, generate *mi* random numbers from the *F**i* distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] In a Bayesian setting, additional levels can be added to the graphical model defining the mixture model.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] For example, in the common latent Dirichlet allocation topic model, the observations are sets of words drawn from *D* different documents and the *K* mixture components represent topics that are shared across documents.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Each document has a different set of mixture weights, which specify the topics prevalent in that document.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] All sets of mixture weights share common hyperparameters.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] A very common extension is to connect the latent variables defining the mixture component identities into a Markov chain, instead of assuming that they are independent identically distributed random variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The resulting model is termed a hidden Markov model and is one of the most common sequential hierarchical models.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Numerous extensions of hidden Markov models have been developed; see the resulting article for more information.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] The motivation for this work was provided by the zoologist Walter Frank Raphael Weldon who had speculated in 1893 (in Tarter and Lock) that asymmetry in the histogram of these ratios could signal evolutionary divergence.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Pearson's approach was to fit a univariate mixture of two normals to the data by choosing the five parameters of the mixture such that the empirical moments matched that of the model.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] While his work was successful in identifying two potentially distinct sub-populations and in demonstrating the flexibility of mixtures as a moment matching tool, the formulation required the solution of a 9th degree (nonic) polynomial which at the time posed a significant computational challenge.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Subsequent works focused on addressing these problems, but it was not until the advent of the modern computer and the popularisation of Maximum Likelihood (MLE) parameterisation techniques that research really took off.
[src:mixture-models-em/gaussian-mixture-model] Since that time there has been a vast body of research on the subject spanning areas such as fisheries research, agriculture, botany, economics, medicine, genetics, psychology, palaeontology, electrophoresis, finance, geology and zoology.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] In statistics, a **latent class model** (**LCM**) is a model for clustering multivariate discrete data.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] It assumes that the data arise from a mixture of discrete distributions, within each of which the variables are independent.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] It is called a latent class model because the class to which each data point belongs is unobserved (or latent).
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] When faced with the following situation, a researcher might opt to use LCA to better understand the data: Symptoms a, b, c, and d have been recorded in a variety of patients diagnosed with diseases X, Y, and Z.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Disease X is associated with symptoms a, b, and c; disease Y is linked to symptoms b, c, and d; and disease Z is connected to symptoms a, c, and d.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] In this context, the LCA would attempt to detect the presence of latent classes (i.e., the disease entities), thus creating patterns of association in the symptoms.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] As in factor analysis, LCA can also be used to classify cases according to their maximum likelihood class membership probability.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] The key criterion for resolving the LCA is identifying latent classes in which the observed symptom associations are effectively rendered null.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] This is because within each class, the diseases responsible for the symptoms create a structure of dependencies.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] As a result, the symptoms become conditionally independent, meaning that, given the class a case belongs to, the symptoms are no longer related to one another.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Within each latent class, the observed variables are statistically independent—an essential aspect of latent class modeling.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Usually, the observed variables are statistically dependent.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] By introducing the latent variable, independence is restored in the sense that within classes, variables are independent (local independence).
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Therefore, the association between the observed variables is explained by the classes of the latent variable (McCutcheon, 1987).
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] where T is the number of latent classes and $p_{t}$ are the so-called recruitment or unconditional probabilities that should sum to one. $p_{i_{n},t}^{n}$ are the marginal or conditional probabilities.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] This two-way model is related to probabilistic latent semantic analysis and non-negative matrix factorization.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] The probability model used in LCA is closely related to the Naive Bayes classifier.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] The main difference is that in LCA, the class membership of an individual is a latent variable, whereas in Naive Bayes classifiers, the class membership is an observed label.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] There are a number of methods with distinct names and uses that share a common relationship.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Cluster analysis is, like LCA, used to discover taxon-like groups of cases in data.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Multivariate mixture estimation (MME) is applicable to continuous data and assumes that such data arise from a mixture of distributions, such as a set of heights arising from a mixture of men and women.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] If a multivariate mixture estimation is constrained so that measures must be uncorrelated within each distribution, it is termed latent profile analysis.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Modified to handle discrete data, this constrained analysis is known as LCA.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Discrete latent trait models further constrain the classes to form from segments of a single dimension, allocating members to classes based on that dimension.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] An example would be assigning cases to social classes based on ability or merit.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] In a practical instance, the variables could be multiple choice items of a political questionnaire.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] In this case, the data consists of an N-way contingency table with answers to the items for a number of respondents.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] In this example, the latent variable refers to political opinion, and the latent classes to political groups.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] Given group membership, the conditional probabilities specify the chance that certain answers are chosen.
[src:mixture-models-em/latent-class-model] LCA may be used in many fields, such as: collaborative filtering, *Behavior Genetics* and Evaluation of diagnostic tests.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The underlying random variables may be random real numbers, or they may be random vectors (each having the same dimension), in which case the mixture distribution is a multivariate distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] In cases where each of the underlying random variables is continuous, the outcome variable will also be continuous and its probability density function is sometimes referred to as a **mixture density**.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The cumulative distribution function (and the probability density function if it exists) can be expressed as a convex combination (i.e. a weighted sum, with non-negative weights that sum to 1) of other distribution functions and density functions.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The individual distributions that are combined to form the mixture distribution are called the **mixture components**, and the probabilities (or weights) associated with each component are called the **mixture weights**.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The number of components in a mixture distribution is often restricted to being finite, although in some cases the components may be countably infinite in number.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] More general cases (i.e. an uncountable set of component distributions), as well as the countable case, are treated under the title of **compound distributions**.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] As an example, the sum of two jointly normally distributed random variables, each with different means, will still have a normal distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] On the other hand, a mixture density created as a mixture of two normal distributions with different means will have two peaks provided that the two means are far enough apart, showing that this distribution is radically different from a normal distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Mixture distributions arise in many contexts in the literature and arise naturally where a statistical population contains two or more subpopulations.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] They are also sometimes used as a means of representing non-normal distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The case of a countably infinite set of components is covered formally by allowing $n=\infty \!$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Where the set of component distributions is uncountable, the result is often called a compound probability distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The construction of such distributions has a formal similarity to that of mixture distributions, with either infinite summations or integrals replacing the finite summations used for finite mixtures.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Consider a probability density function *p*(*x*;*a*) for a variable x, parameterized by a.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] That is, for each value of a in some set A, *p*(*x*;*a*) is a probability density function with respect to x.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] is again a probability density function for x.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] A similar integral can be written for the cumulative distribution function.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Note that the formulae here reduce to the case of a finite or infinite mixture if the density w is allowed to be a generalized function representing the "derivative" of the cumulative distribution function of a discrete distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The mixture components are often not arbitrary probability distributions, but instead are members of a parametric family (such as normal distributions), with different values for a parameter or parameters.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] A general linear combination of probability density functions is not necessarily a probability density, since it may be negative or it may integrate to something other than 1.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] However, a convex combination of probability density functions preserves both of these properties (non-negativity and integrating to 1), and thus mixture densities are themselves probability density functions.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Let *X*1, ..., *X**n* denote random variables from the n component distributions, and let X denote a random variable from the mixture distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The jth moment about zero (i.e. choosing *H*(*x*) = *x**j*) is simply a weighted average of the j-th moments of the components.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] where *μi* denotes the mean of the i-th component.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] These relations highlight the potential of mixture distributions to display non-trivial higher-order moments such as skewness and kurtosis (fat tails) and multi-modality, even in the absence of such features within the components themselves.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Marron and Wand (1992) give an illustrative account of the flexibility of this framework.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The question of multimodality is simple for some cases, such as mixtures of exponential distributions: all such mixtures are unimodal.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] However, for the case of mixtures of normal distributions, it is a complex one.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Conditions for the number of modes in a multivariate normal mixture are explored by Ray & Lindsay extending earlier work on univariate and multivariate distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Using graphical tools, the potential multi-modality of mixtures with number of components $n\in \{2,3\}$ is demonstrated; in particular it is shown that the number of modes may exceed n and that the modes may not be coincident with the component means.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Since the above is quadratic it follows that in this instance there are at most two modes irrespective of the dimension or the weights.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] For normal mixtures with general $n>2$ and $D>1$ , a lower bound for the maximum number of possible modes, and – conditionally on the assumption that the maximum number is finite – an upper bound are known.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] For those combinations of n and D for which the maximum number is known, it matches the lower bound.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Simple examples can be given by a mixture of two normal distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] If sufficiently separated, namely by twice the (common) standard deviation, so $\left|\mu _{1}-\mu _{2}\right|>2\sigma ,$ these form a bimodal distribution, otherwise it simply has a wide peak.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Alternatively, given two subpopulations with the same mean and different standard deviations, the overall population will exhibit high kurtosis, with a sharper peak and heavier tails (and correspondingly shallower shoulders) than a single distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The following example is adapted from Hampel, who credits John Tukey.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The mean of i.i.d. observations from *F*(*x*) behaves "normally" except for exorbitantly large samples, although the mean of *F*(*x*) does not even exist.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Mixture densities can be used to model a statistical population with subpopulations, where the mixture components are the densities on the subpopulations, and the weights are the proportions of each subpopulation in the overall population.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Mixture densities can also be used to model experimental error or contamination – one assumes that most of the samples measure the desired phenomenon, with some samples from a different, erroneous distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] Parametric statistics that assume no error often fail on such mixture densities – for example, statistics that assume normality often fail disastrously in the presence of even a few outliers – and instead one uses robust statistics.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] In meta-analysis of separate studies, study heterogeneity causes distribution of results to be a mixture distribution, and leads to overdispersion of results relative to predicted error.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] For example, in a statistical survey, the margin of error (determined by sample size) predicts the sampling error and hence dispersion of results on repeated surveys.
[src:mixture-models-em/mixture-distribution] The presence of study heterogeneity (studies have different sampling bias) increases the dispersion relative to the margin of error.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] In statistics, cluster analysis is the algorithmic grouping of objects into homogeneous groups based on numerical measurements.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] **Model-based clustering** based on a statistical model for the data, usually a mixture model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] This has several advantages, including a principled statistical basis for clustering, and ways to choose the number of clusters, to choose the best clustering model, to assess the uncertainty of the clustering, and to identify outliers that do not belong to any group.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Suppose that for each of n observations we have data on d variables, denoted by $y_{i}=(y_{i,1},\ldots ,y_{i,d})$ for observation i .
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] where $f_{g}$ is a probability density function with parameter $\theta _{g}$ , $\tau _{g}$ is the corresponding mixture probability where $\sum _{g=1}^{G}\tau _{g}=1$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Then in its simplest form, model-based clustering views each component of the mixture model as a cluster, estimates the model parameters, and assigns each observation to cluster corresponding to its most likely mixture component.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The most common model for continuous data is that $f_{g}$ is a multivariate normal distribution with mean vector $\mu _{g}$ and covariance matrix $\Sigma _{g}$ , so that $\theta _{g}=(\mu _{g},\Sigma _{g})$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The parameters of the model, $\tau _{g}$ and $\theta _{g}$ for $g=1,\ldots ,G$ , are typically estimated by maximum likelihood estimation using the expectation-maximization algorithm (EM); see also EM algorithm and GMM model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Bayesian inference is also often used for inference about finite mixture models.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The Bayesian approach also allows for the case where the number of components, G , is infinite, using a Dirichlet process prior, yielding a Dirichlet process mixture model for clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] An advantage of model-based clustering is that it provides statistically principled ways to choose the number of clusters.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Each different choice of the number of groups G corresponds to a different mixture model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Then standard statistical model selection criteria such as the Bayesian information criterion (BIC) can be used to choose G .
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The integrated completed likelihood (ICL) is a different criterion designed to choose the number of clusters rather than the number of mixture components in the model; these will often be different if highly non-Gaussian clusters are present.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] For data with high dimension, d , using a full covariance matrix for each mixture component requires estimation of many parameters, which can result in a loss of precision, generalizabity and interpretability.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Thus it is common to use more parsimonious component covariance matrices exploiting their geometric interpretation.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Gaussian clusters are ellipsoidal, with their volume, shape and orientation determined by the covariance matrix.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] where $D_{g}$ is the matrix of eigenvectors of $\Sigma _{g}$ , $A_{g}={\mbox{diag}}\{A_{1,g},\ldots ,A_{d,g}\}$ is a diagonal matrix whose elements are proportional to the eigenvalues of $\Sigma _{g}$ in descending order, and $\lambda _{g}$ is the associated constant of proportionality.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Then $\lambda _{g}$ controls the volume of the ellipsoid, $A_{g}$ its shape, and $D_{g}$ its orientation.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Each of the volume, shape and orientation of the clusters can be constrained to be equal (E) or allowed to vary (V); the orientation can also be spherical, with identical eigenvalues (I).
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] It can be seen that many of these models are more parsimonious, with far fewer parameters than the unconstrained model that has 90 parameters when $G=4$ and $d=9$ .
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Several of these models correspond to well-known heuristic clustering methods.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] For example, k-means clustering is equivalent to estimation of the EII clustering model using the classification EM algorithm.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The Bayesian information criterion (BIC) can be used to choose the best clustering model as well as the number of clusters.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] It can also be used as the basis for a method to choose the variables in the clustering model, eliminating variables that are not useful for clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Different Gaussian model-based clustering methods have been developed with an eye to handling high-dimensional data.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] These include the pgmm method, which is based on the mixture of factor analyzers model, and the HDclassif method, based on the idea of subspace clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The mixture-of-experts framework extends model-based clustering to include covariates.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] We illustrate the method with a dateset consisting of three measurements (glucose, insulin, sspg) on 145 subjects for the purpose of diagnosing diabetes and the type of diabetes present.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The subjects were clinically classified into three groups: normal, chemical diabetes and overt diabetes, but we use this information only for evaluating clustering methods, not for classifying subjects.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The BIC plot shows the BIC values for each combination of the number of clusters, G , and the clustering model from the Table.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Each curve corresponds to a different clustering model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The BIC favors 3 groups, which corresponds to the clinical assessment.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] It also favors the unconstrained covariance model, VVV.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] This fits the data well, because the normal patients have low values of both sspg and insulin, while the distributions of the chemical and overt diabetes groups are elongated, but in different directions.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Thus the volumes, shapes and orientations of the three groups are clearly different, and so the unconstrained model is appropriate, as selected by the model-based clustering method.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The classification plot shows the classification of the subjects by model-based clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The classification was quite accurate, with a 12% error rate as defined by the clinical classification.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Other well-known clustering methods performed worse with higher error rates, such as single-linkage clustering with 46%, average link clustering with 30%, complete-linkage clustering also with 30%, and k-means clustering with 28%.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] An outlier in clustering is a data point that does not belong to any of the clusters.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] One way of modeling outliers in model-based clustering is to include an additional mixture component that is very dispersed, with for example a uniform distribution.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Another approach is to replace the multivariate normal densities by t -distributions, with the idea that the long tails of the t -distribution would ensure robustness to outliers.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] A third approach is the "tclust" or data trimming approach which excludes observations identified as outliers when estimating the model parameters.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Sometimes one or more clusters deviate strongly from the Gaussian assumption.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] If a Gaussian mixture is fitted to such data, a strongly non-Gaussian cluster will often be represented by several mixture components rather than a single one.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] In that case, cluster merging can be used to find a better clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] A different approach is to use mixtures of complex component densities to represent non-Gaussian clusters.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Clustering multivariate categorical data is most often done using the latent class model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] This assumes that the data arise from a finite mixture model, where within each cluster the variables are independent.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] These arise when variables are of different types, such as continuous, categorical or ordinal data.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] A latent class model for mixed data assumes local independence between the variable.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The location model relaxes the local independence assumption.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The clustMD approach assumes that the observed variables are manifestations of underlying continuous Gaussian latent variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The simplest model-based clustering approach for multivariate count data is based on finite mixtures with locally independent Poisson distributions, similar to the latent class model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] More realistic approaches allow for dependence and overdispersion in the counts.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] These include methods based on the multivariate Poisson distribution, the multivarate Poisson-log normal distribution, the integer-valued autoregressive (INAR) model and the Gaussian Cox model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] These consist of sequences of categorical values from a finite set of possibilities, such as life course trajectories.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Model-based clustering approaches include group-based trajectory and growth mixture models and a distance-based mixture model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] These arise when individuals rank objects in order of preference.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The data are then ordered lists of objects, arising in voting, education, marketing and other areas.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Model-based clustering methods for rank data include mixtures of Plackett-Luce models and mixtures of Benter models, and mixtures of Mallows models.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] These consist of the presence, absence or strength of connections between individuals or nodes, and are widespread in the social sciences and biology.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The stochastic blockmodel carries out model-based clustering of the nodes in a network by assuming that there is a latent clustering and that connections are formed independently given the clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The latent position cluster model assumes that each node occupies a position in an unobserved latent space, that these positions arise from a mixture of Gaussian distributions, and that presence or absence of a connection is associated with distance in the latent space.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Much of the model-based clustering software is in the form of a publicly and freely available R package.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Many of these are listed in the CRAN Task View on Cluster Analysis and Finite Mixture Models.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The most used such package is mclust, which is used to cluster continuous data and has been downloaded over 8 million times.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The poLCA package clusters categorical data using the latent class model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The clustMD package clusters mixed data, including continuous, binary, ordinal and nominal variables.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The flexmix package does model-based clustering for a range of component distributions.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] The mixtools package can cluster different data types.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Both flexmix and mixtools implement model-based clustering with covariates.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Model-based clustering was first invented in 1950 by Paul Lazarsfeld for clustering multivariate discrete data, in the form of the latent class model.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] In 1959, Lazarsfeld gave a lecture on latent structure analysis at the University of California-Berkeley, where John H.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] This led Wolfe to think about how to do the same thing for continuous data, and in 1965 he did so, proposing the Gaussian mixture model for clustering.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] He also produced the first software for estimating it, called NORMIX.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Day (1969), working independently, was the first to publish a journal article on the approach.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] However, Wolfe deserves credit as the inventor of model-based clustering for continuous data.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Murtagh and Raftery (1984) developed a model-based clustering method based on the eigenvalue decomposition of the component covariance matrices.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] McLachlan and Basford (1988) was the first book on the approach, advancing methodology and sparking interest.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Banfield and Raftery (1993) coined the term "model-based clustering", introduced the family of parsimonious models, described an information criterion for choosing the number of clusters, proposed the uniform model for outliers, and introduced the mclust software.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Celeux and Govaert (1995) showed how to perform maximum likelihood estimation for the models.
[src:mixture-models-em/model-based-clustering] Thus, by 1995 the core components of the methodology were in place, laying the groundwork for extensive development since then.
